instructions:
## Set up Nginx as a reverse proxy for Node.js / Next.js

### 1. Pre-flight checks
- Confirm you have a VPS with Ubuntu 22.04+ or Debian 12+ and a public IP address.
- Confirm your domain's DNS `A` record points to the VPS IP. Check with: `dig +short yourdomain.com`.
- Confirm your Node.js app is running and listening on `localhost:3000` (or another port).
- Check if Nginx is already installed: `nginx -v`. If not, install it.
- Check if port 80 and 443 are open in the VPS firewall/security group.

### 2. Install Nginx
```bash
sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y nginx
sudo systemctl enable nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx
```
- Verify Nginx is running: `sudo systemctl status nginx`
- Verify port 80 is reachable: `curl -I http://yourdomain.com` should return an Nginx default page.

### 3. Configure UFW firewall (if applicable)
```bash
sudo ufw allow 'Nginx Full'   # opens ports 80 and 443
sudo ufw allow OpenSSH        # keep SSH accessible
sudo ufw enable
sudo ufw status
```
- `Nginx Full` is an app profile that allows both HTTP and HTTPS. NEVER enable `Nginx HTTPS` alone before SSL is configured — it will lock you out of HTTP needed by Certbot.

### 4. Create the Nginx server block
- Create `/etc/nginx/sites-available/yourdomain.com`:
```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;
    server_name yourdomain.com www.yourdomain.com;

    # Redirect all HTTP to HTTPS (added after cert issuance)
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl http2;
    listen [::]:443 ssl http2;
    server_name yourdomain.com www.yourdomain.com;

    # SSL — paths populated by Certbot
    ssl_certificate     /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/privkey.pem;
    include             /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf;
    ssl_dhparam         /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem;

    # Security headers
    add_header X-Frame-Options           "SAMEORIGIN" always;
    add_header X-Content-Type-Options    "nosniff" always;
    add_header X-XSS-Protection          "1; mode=block" always;
    add_header Referrer-Policy           "strict-origin-when-cross-origin" always;
    add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains" always;

    # Gzip compression
    gzip on;
    gzip_vary on;
    gzip_proxied any;
    gzip_comp_level 6;
    gzip_types text/plain text/css application/json application/javascript
               text/xml application/xml application/xml+rss text/javascript
               image/svg+xml;

    # Rate limiting (defined in nginx.conf http block)
    limit_req zone=app burst=20 nodelay;

    # Proxy to Node.js app
    location / {
        proxy_pass         http://127.0.0.1:3000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header   Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header   Connection 'upgrade';
        proxy_set_header   Host $host;
        proxy_set_header   X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header   X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header   X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
        proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
        proxy_read_timeout 90;
    }

    # Next.js static assets — long cache
    location /_next/static/ {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000/_next/static/;
        add_header Cache-Control "public, max-age=31536000, immutable";
    }

    # Serve public/ files directly (optional, improves performance)
    location /favicon.ico {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000/favicon.ico;
        add_header Cache-Control "public, max-age=86400";
    }
}
```
- Replace `yourdomain.com` with your actual domain everywhere.
- Replace `3000` with your app's actual port.
- The `Upgrade` / `Connection` proxy headers are needed for WebSocket support.

### 5. Add rate limiting to the main Nginx config
- Open `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf` and add inside the `http { }` block:
```nginx
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=app:10m rate=30r/s;
```
- `30r/s` with `burst=20` allows bursts of 20 requests while smoothing to 30 req/s overall. Adjust to your app's needs.

### 6. Enable the site
```bash
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/yourdomain.com /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
sudo nginx -t          # test config — must say 'syntax is ok'
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```
- Always run `nginx -t` before reloading. A config error will take down the entire Nginx service on reload.
- Do NOT enable the SSL server block yet — the cert files don't exist. Start with just the HTTP block.

### 7. Obtain SSL certificate with Certbot
```bash
sudo apt install -y certbot python3-certbot-nginx
sudo certbot --nginx -d yourdomain.com -d www.yourdomain.com
```
- Certbot will automatically edit your Nginx config to add SSL paths and set up HTTP→HTTPS redirect.
- Provide an email address for expiry notifications.
- Choose to redirect all HTTP traffic to HTTPS when prompted.
- Certbot installs a systemd timer for automatic renewal: `sudo systemctl status certbot.timer`.
- Test renewal: `sudo certbot renew --dry-run`.

### 8. Verify final state
```bash
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl reload nginx
curl -I https://yourdomain.com      # should return HTTP/2 200
curl -I http://yourdomain.com       # should redirect 301 to HTTPS
```
- Check headers with: `curl -I https://yourdomain.com | grep -E 'Strict|X-Frame|Content-Type'`
- Test SSL rating at `https://www.ssllabs.com/ssltest/` — target grade A.

### 9. Process management for the Node.js app
- Use PM2 to keep the app running:
```bash
npm install -g pm2
pm2 start npm --name "app" -- start   # or: pm2 start dist/index.js --name app
pm2 save
pm2 startup   # follow the printed command to enable on boot
```
- Check status: `pm2 status`
- View logs: `pm2 logs app`
- For Next.js: `pm2 start npm --name "nextjs" -- start` (runs `next start`)

### Common errors & fixes
- **`502 Bad Gateway`** → The Node.js app is not running or is not listening on the correct port/host. Check with `curl http://localhost:3000` directly on the server.
- **`nginx -t` fails after Certbot edit** → Certbot may have duplicated `server_name` or `listen` directives. Inspect the file carefully and remove duplicates.
- **Certbot fails with `Problem binding to port 80`** → Something else is on port 80. Check: `sudo ss -tlnp | grep :80`. Apache may be running alongside Nginx.
- **`413 Request Entity Too Large`** → Set `client_max_body_size 50M;` in the `server` or `location` block.
- **WebSocket connections failing** → Ensure the `Upgrade` and `Connection` headers are set in the proxy block. Check that your app's WebSocket server is on the same port as the HTTP server.
- **ERR_TOO_MANY_REDIRECTS** → App is sending its own HTTP→HTTPS redirect while Nginx is also redirecting. Set `NEXTAUTH_URL`, `APP_URL`, etc. to `https://` and ensure the app trusts `X-Forwarded-Proto`.
- **Certbot renewal fails** → Port 80 may be blocked by firewall. Ensure `ufw` allows Nginx Full.
- **Static files returning 404** → Check that the `proxy_pass` for `/_next/static/` includes the trailing slash on both sides.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT expose the Node.js port (3000) directly to the internet. Bind the app to `127.0.0.1:3000`, not `0.0.0.0:3000`.
- Do NOT skip `nginx -t` before reloading — a syntax error will cause all sites on the server to go down.
- Do NOT use self-signed certificates in production. Use Let's Encrypt (free) or a paid cert.
- Do NOT set `proxy_pass http://localhost:3000` — prefer `127.0.0.1` to avoid IPv4/IPv6 resolution ambiguity.
- Do NOT forget to open ports 80 and 443 in cloud provider security groups (AWS, GCP, DigitalOcean) — UFW alone is not enough if the cloud firewall blocks them.
- Do NOT add `Strict-Transport-Security` with `includeSubDomains` if you have HTTP subdomains — it will break them.
- Do NOT run Nginx and Apache on the same server without careful port management.
